title: [Mac] Recent changes in the "hamburger menu"/History/Recently closed tabs function?
content:
Hello,

In multi-window browser sessions on Linux, the "Recently closed tabs" menu shows a list of URLs relevant to the parent (aka current) window, and that is both perfectly logical and highly useful. It makes it a lot easier to find that specific URL you're looking for, if not only because it increases the chance that it hasn't yet been flushed out of the recently-closed list.

I have a very distinct memory that this was the case on Mac too for the URLs showed by this menu when accessed via the "hamburger menu". I'm positive that I accessed the function via the hamburger menu rather than the faster way via the menubar for that very reason. And I just realised that it's no longer possible starting with at least v143.

With the Mac's global menu bar it would stand to reason that it presents lists that are "global" to the session, but I see no good *usability* reason that would justify *not* using window-specific lists under the hamburger menu.

One could of course argue that it's confusing and a "burden" to the user that s/he would need to remember in which window the looked-for tab once lived. But that argument would apply to all platforms, and this is supposed to be about *recently* closed tabs and one has to assume that the majority of users have no issue remembering in which window they have (or had!) a given tab open. (And that otherwise they'd be using a singe window, probably maximised to occupy the entire screen ;) ).

title: Firefox Takes Long to Load a Specific Client Service Page After Recent Update
content:
Hi everyone,

After the most recent Firefox update, I started noticing that one specific service page from a client site loads unusually slow only in Firefox. Other pages on the same domain load fine, and the same page opens instantly in Chrome and Edge.

The slowdown happens on the Buffalo Airport Taxi & Limousine Service Buffalo Airport Taxi & Limousine Service page . The page does eventually load, but the initial connection hangs for a few seconds before anything appears. Once it‚Äôs cached, the speed improves, but the first load is consistently slow.

I‚Äôve already tried: ‚Ä¢ Clearing the cache ‚Ä¢ Restarting the browser ‚Ä¢ Disabling all extensions ‚Ä¢ Testing in Private mode ‚Ä¢ Flushing DNS and changing DNS servers

The strange part is that everything on the server side looks normal, and network diagnostics show no issue. This seems to have started right after the Firefox update, so I‚Äôm wondering if there‚Äôs something related to SSL, connection negotiation, or new caching behaviour in this version.

Has anyone else seen Firefox slow down on specific pages after updating? Any settings or flags I should check?

Thanks in advance.

I'm over 60 and I didn't read as much (as I should have, since I was younger) my reading comprehension isn't that great. Thank you for reading, Roger Erickson
